{"title_page": "Joseph Jekyll (1754\u20131837)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n'''Joseph Jekyll''' [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (1 January 1754 \u2013 8 March 1837) was a British Member of Parliament for Calne, Wiltshire.\n\nHe was the eldest son of Capt. Edward Jekyll, R.N., of Haverfordwest and educated at [[Westminster School]] (1766\u20131770) and [[Christ Church, Oxford]], where he was awarded BA in 1774 and MA in 1777. He trained for the law at [[Lincoln's Inn]] from 1769 and was [[called to the bar]] in 1778.\n\nHe was elected in 1790 a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] as \"''a Gentleman conversant in various Branches of Literature''\".<ref>{{cite web| url= http://royalsociety.org/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqSearch=RefNo==%27EC%2F1790%2F07%27&dsqCmd=Show.tcl|title = Library Archive|publisher= Royal Society|accessdate =2014-02-21}}</ref>\n\nHe was made Bencher at the [[Inner Temple]] in 1805, reader in 1814 and treasurer in 1816. He was appointed solicitor-general to the Prince of Wales and made [[King's Counsel]] in 1805.\n\nIn 1787 he was elected Member of Parliament for [[Calne (UK Parliament constituency)|Calne]], a seat he held until 1816, after which he resigned by accepting the notional crown appointment as [[Steward of the Chiltern Hundreds]].\n\nIn 1824, Joseph inherited the [[Wargrave]] Hill (now Wargrave Manor) estate in [[Berkshire]], although he preferred to live in Mayfair and so rented it out to tenants. He died in London in 1837. He had married in 1801 Maria, the daughter of MP [[Hans Sloane (MP)|Hans Sloane]], with whom he had two sons. The youngest was the father of the garden designer, [[Gertrude Jekyll]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{cite web | url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/jekyll-joseph-1754-1837| title = JEKYLL, Joseph (1754\u20131837).| publisher= History of Parliament Online|accessdate = 2014-02-21}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jekyll, Joseph}}\n[[Category:1754 births]]\n[[Category:1837 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ Church, Oxford]]\n[[Category:People from Mayfair]]\n[[Category:Members of the Inner Temple]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1784\u20131790]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1790\u20131796]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1796\u20131800]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1801\u20131802]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1802\u20131806]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1812\u20131818]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People educated at Westminster School, London]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Society of Antiquaries of London]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:Queen's Counsel 1801\u20131900]]\n[[Category:English writers]]\n\n\n{{England-UK-MP-stub}}\n{{England-GreatBritain-MP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n'''Joseph Jekyll''' [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (1 January 1754 \u2013 8 March 1837) was a British Member of Parliament for Calne, Wiltshire.\n\nHe was the eldest son of Capt. Edward Jekyll, R.N., of Haverfordwest and educated at [[Westminster School]] (1766\u20131770) and [[Christ Church, Oxford]], where he was awarded BA in 1774 and MA in 1777. He trained for the law at [[Lincoln's Inn]] from 1769 and was [[called to the bar]] in 1778.\n\nHe was elected in 1790 a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] as \"''a Gentleman conversant in various Branches of Literature''\".<ref>{{cite web| url= http://royalsociety.org/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqSearch=RefNo==%27EC%2F1790%2F07%27&dsqCmd=Show.tcl|title = Library Archive|publisher= Royal Society|accessdate =2014-02-21}}</ref>\n\nHe was made Bencher at the [[Inner Temple]] in 1805, reader in 1814 and treasurer in 1816. He was appointed solicitor-general to the Prince of Wales and made [[King's Counsel]] in 1805.\n\nIn 1787 he was elected Member of Parliament for [[Calne (UK Parliament constituency)|Calne]], a seat he held until 1816, after which he resigned by accepting the notional crown appointment as [[Steward of the Chiltern Hundreds]].\n\nIn 1824, Joseph inherited the [[Wargrave]] Hill (now Wargrave Manor) estate in [[Berkshire]], although he preferred to live in Mayfair and so rented it out to tenants. He died in London in 1837. He had married in 1801 Maria, the daughter of MP [[Hans Sloane (MP)|Hans Sloane]], with whom he had two sons. The youngest was the father of the garden designer, [[Gertrude Jekyll]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{cite web | url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/jekyll-joseph-1754-1837| title = JEKYLL, Joseph (1754\u20131837).| publisher= History of Parliament Online|accessdate = 2014-02-21}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jekyll, Joseph}}\n[[Category:1754 births]]\n[[Category:1837 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ Church, Oxford]]\n[[Category:People from Mayfair]]\n[[Category:Members of the Inner Temple]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1784\u20131790]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1790\u20131796]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1796\u20131800]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1801\u20131802]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1802\u20131806]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1812\u20131818]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People educated at Westminster School, London]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Society of Antiquaries of London]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:Queen's Counsel 1801\u20131900]]\n[[Category:English writers]]\n\n\n{{England-UK-MP-stub}}\n{{England-GreatBritain-MP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences